78.1 The R Concept
A full analytical pipeline chains every relevant verb together, each one passing its result to the next:
result &lt;- df |&gt;
  filter(condition) |&gt;
  group_by(grouping_column) |&gt;
  summarise(stat = &lt;function&gt;(column, na.rm = TRUE)) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(stat))
Each step in this chain does exactly one job — filter narrows the rows, group_by() sets up per-group processing, summarise() collapses each group to one row, and arrange() orders the final result — and the pipe (|&gt;) makes the whole sequence read top-to-bottom, in the order the steps actually happen.

85.1 The R Concept
A reshaping pipeline often goes wide → long → (filter/analyze) → wide again: long format makes it easy to filter() down to exactly the visits you want, and pivoting back to wide afterward aligns the remaining visits side by side so you can compute a per-row difference with mutate():
df |&gt;
  pivot_longer(cols = ..., names_to = "visit", values_to = "value") |&gt;
  filter(visit %in% c("first_visit", "last_visit")) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = visit, values_from = value) |&gt;
  mutate(change = last_visit - first_visit)

85.4 Solve the Problem

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

bp_wide &lt;- read.csv("data/bp_visits_wide.csv")

county_change_summary &lt;- bp_wide |&gt;
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("sbp_visit"), names_to = "visit", names_prefix = "sbp_", values_to = "sbp") |&gt;
  filter(visit %in% c("visit1", "visit3")) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = visit, values_from = sbp) |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(visit3)) |&gt;
  mutate(change = visit3 - visit1) |&gt;
  group_by(county) |&gt;
  summarise(n = n(), mean_change = round(mean(change), 2)) |&gt;
  arrange(mean_change)

county_change_summary

# A tibble: 5 x 3
  county          n mean_change
  &lt;chr&gt;       &lt;int&gt;       &lt;dbl&gt;
1 Springvale      6      -10.17
2 Cedar Falls     4       -8.00
3 Millbrook       4       -3.50
4 Riverdale       6       -2.67
5 Oakford         6       -1.17
Springvale shows the largest average blood pressure decrease from visit 1 to visit 3 (-10.17), followed by Cedar Falls (-8.00) — though Cedar Falls’ figure rests on just 4 complete participants and Millbrook’s on only 4 as well (2 of Millbrook’s 6 participants dropped out before visit 3).

91.4 Solve the Problem

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

bp_wide &lt;- read.csv("data/bp_visits_wide.csv")
baseline &lt;- read.csv("data/baseline_enrollment.csv")

bp_change &lt;- bp_wide |&gt;
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("sbp_visit"), names_to = "visit", names_prefix = "sbp_", values_to = "sbp") |&gt;
  filter(visit %in% c("visit1", "visit3")) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = visit, values_from = sbp) |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(visit3)) |&gt;
  mutate(change = visit3 - visit1)

bp_change_with_age &lt;- bp_change |&gt;
  left_join(baseline[, c("id", "age")], by = "id") |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(age)) |&gt;
  mutate(age_group = ifelse(age &gt;= 50, "50+", "Under 50"))

age_group_summary &lt;- bp_change_with_age |&gt;
  group_by(age_group) |&gt;
  summarise(n = n(), mean_change = round(mean(change), 2)) |&gt;
  arrange(age_group)

age_group_summary

# A tibble: 2 x 3
  age_group     n mean_change
  &lt;chr&gt;     &lt;int&gt;       &lt;dbl&gt;
1 50+           7       -1.86
2 Under 50      9       -8.56
Among the 16 participants with usable age and complete visit data, those under 50 show a much larger average blood pressure decrease (-8.56) than those 50 and older (-1.86) — the opposite of what you might have guessed, and a good reminder to report a surprising pattern rather than dismiss it, while still treating it cautiously (n=7 and n=9 are both small groups).

112.1 The R Concept
A function is created with the function() keyword, listing its argument names in parentheses, followed by a block of code in curly braces {}:
function_name &lt;- function(argument1, argument2) {
  # code using argument1 and argument2
  result   # the last evaluated expression is returned automatically
}
R automatically returns whatever the last line of the function evaluates to — no explicit return() needed, though it’s allowed and sometimes used for clarity or to exit early:
pct_missing &lt;- function(x) {
  sum(is.na(x)) / length(x) * 100
}

113.1 The R Concept
A default argument value is specified with = directly in the function definition, and is used automatically whenever that argument is omitted from the call:
function_name &lt;- function(x, digits = 2) {
  # digits is 2 unless the caller specifies otherwise
}
describe_numeric &lt;- function(x, digits = 2) {
  c(
    mean = round(mean(x, na.rm = TRUE), digits),
    sd = round(sd(x, na.rm = TRUE), digits)
  )
}
Calling describe_numeric(participants$age) uses digits = 2 automatically; calling describe_numeric(participants$age, digits = 0) overrides it explicitly. This is exactly the same pattern behind mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)’s na.rm argument, which defaults to FALSE unless you explicitly set it to TRUE.

114.1 The R Concept
A function’s body can contain the exact same if/else if/else logic (Level 4) you’d use outside a function — the only difference is that the result becomes the function’s return value:
classify &lt;- function(x) {
  if (x &lt; threshold1) {
    "Category A"
  } else if (x &lt; threshold2) {
    "Category B"
  } else {
    "Category C"
  }
}
bp_category &lt;- function(sbp) {
  if (sbp &lt; 120) {
    "Normal"
  } else if (sbp &lt; 130) {
    "Elevated"
  } else if (sbp &lt; 140) {
    "Stage 1"
  } else {
    "Stage 2"
  }
}
Whichever branch actually runs becomes the function’s return value automatically — R returns the last evaluated expression, exactly as on Page 2, and here that last expression differs depending on which if/else if branch was taken.

114.2 Demonstration

bp_category &lt;- function(sbp) {
  if (sbp &lt; 120) {
    "Normal"
  } else if (sbp &lt; 130) {
    "Elevated"
  } else if (sbp &lt; 140) {
