bp_categories
Elevated   Normal  Stage 1  Stage 2
      18       32       17       29
Exactly the same category counts (18 Elevated, 32 Normal, 17 Stage 1, 29 Stage 2) as Level 4’s case_when()-based mutate() produced on the full data frame — confirming the function-based, single-value approach and the data-frame-wide case_when() approach agree perfectly.

115.1 The R Concept
A function can accept as many arguments as it needs, listed in order, separated by commas:
function_name &lt;- function(arg1, arg2) {
  # code using both arg1 and arg2
}
is_at_risk &lt;- function(age, sbp, age_cutoff = 65, bp_cutoff = 130) {
  age &gt;= age_cutoff & sbp &gt;= bp_cutoff
}
Notice is_at_risk() combines two required arguments (age, sbp) with two optional, default-valued arguments (age_cutoff, bp_cutoff, Page 3) — a function can freely mix both kinds.

120.1 The R Concept
stop() immediately halts a function’s execution and raises an error with a custom message — appropriate when the function genuinely cannot produce a meaningful result:
if (some_bad_condition) {
  stop("A clear message explaining what went wrong")
}
warning() prints a caution message but lets the function continue running — appropriate for situations worth flagging but not necessarily fatal:
if (some_concerning_condition) {
  warning("A message noting something worth double-checking")
}

120.2 Demonstration

pct_missing &lt;- function(x) {
  if (length(x) == 0) {
    stop("x has length 0 - cannot compute percent missing")
  }
  sum(is.na(x)) / length(x) * 100
}

pct_missing(numeric(0))

Error in pct_missing(numeric(0)) : x has length 0 - cannot compute percent missing
Instead of silently returning a confusing NaN, the function now stops immediately with a message explaining exactly what went wrong — much easier to debug than discovering an unexplained NaN several steps later in a report.

120.4 Solve the Problem

pct_missing &lt;- function(x) {
  if (length(x) == 0) {
    stop("x has length 0 - cannot compute percent missing")
  }
  if (all(is.na(x))) {
    warning("Every value in x is missing - result will be 100")
  }
  sum(is.na(x)) / length(x) * 100
}

participants &lt;- read.csv("data/participants.csv")

pct_missing(participants$age)

[1] 6

pct_missing(c(NA, NA, NA))

Warning message:
In pct_missing(c(NA, NA, NA)) : Every value in x is missing - result will be 100
[1] 100

pct_missing(numeric(0))

Error in pct_missing(numeric(0)) : x has length 0 - cannot compute percent missing
Three different inputs, three different appropriate responses: a valid column runs normally (6%), an all-missing vector runs but with a warning attached (100%, flagged as worth double-checking), and a genuinely invalid empty vector stops execution entirely with a clear explanation.

121.1 The R Concept
A complete, well-built function combines every idea from this level: input validation (Page 10) first, then conditional logic (Page 4) branching on the input’s type, using default arguments (Page 3) for adjustable behavior, all wrapped as one named, reusable tool (Page 2) that can be applied across many columns at once (Page 8-9):
column_report &lt;- function(x, digits = 2) {
  if (length(x) == 0) {
    stop("x has length 0 - cannot build a report")
  }
  pct_miss &lt;- round(sum(is.na(x)) / length(x) * 100, digits)

  if (is.numeric(x)) {
    paste0("numeric | ", pct_miss, "% missing | mean = ",
           round(mean(x, na.rm = TRUE), digits), ", sd = ",
           round(sd(x, na.rm = TRUE), digits))
  } else {
    paste0("character | ", pct_miss, "% missing | ",
           length(unique(x[!is.na(x)])), " unique values")
  }
}

