[1] "numeric | 6% missing | mean = 47.43, sd = 15.03"

column_report(participants$county)

[1] "character | 0% missing | 5 unique values"
One function, correctly branching between numeric and character summaries depending entirely on the column’s type — exactly the behavior your professor asked for.

122.1 The R Concept
A for loop repeats a block of code once for every element in a vector, giving each element a temporary name you choose:
for (item in vector) {
  # code using item, repeated once per element of vector
}
Each time through the loop, item takes on the next value in vector, in order, until every element has been used once.

125.1 The R Concept
Looping over a data frame’s columns means looping over its column names, then using double-bracket indexing (df[[col_name]]) to access each column’s actual values — df$col_name doesn’t work here, because $ requires the literal column name typed directly, not a variable holding that name as text:
for (col_name in names(df)) {
  column_values &lt;- df[[col_name]]
  # code using column_values
}

126.1 The R Concept
A nested loop places one for loop entirely inside another — the inner loop runs completely, start to finish, for every single iteration of the outer loop:
for (outer_item in outer_vector) {
  for (inner_item in inner_vector) {
    # runs once for every combination of outer_item and inner_item
  }
}
If the outer loop has n items and the inner loop has m items, the innermost code runs n * m times in total.

126.2 Demonstration

counties &lt;- c("Cedar Falls", "Millbrook")
smoking_statuses &lt;- c("No", "Yes")

for (county in counties) {
  for (status in smoking_statuses) {
    print(paste(county, "-", status))
  }
}

[1] "Cedar Falls - No"
[1] "Cedar Falls - Yes"
[1] "Millbrook - No"
[1] "Millbrook - Yes"
With 2 counties and 2 smoking statuses, the inner loop’s code ran 2 × 2 = 4 times total — notice the inner loop (status) completes both of its values before the outer loop (county) advances to its next value.

153.1 The R Concept
S3 is R’s simplest object system: any list can be turned into an object of a custom “class” just by tagging it with class(). Once tagged, generic functions like print() automatically look for a matching method named print.&lt;classname&gt;:
make_result &lt;- function(value) {
  structure(list(value = value), class = "my_class")
}

print.my_class &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  cat("A my_class object with value:", x$value, "\n")
}
structure() attaches the class attribute while building the list in one step. This is exactly how lm()’s tidy printout works — it’s an ordinary list tagged class = "lm", with a print.lm() method behind the scenes.

153.2 Demonstration

make_risk_summary &lt;- function(participant_id, age, sbp, at_risk) {
  structure(
    list(participant_id = participant_id, age = age, sbp = sbp, at_risk = at_risk),
    class = "risk_summary"
  )
}

print.risk_summary &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  status &lt;- if (x$at_risk) "AT RISK" else "not at risk"
  cat(sprintf("Participant %d (age %d, SBP %d): %s\n", x$participant_id, x$age, x$sbp, status))
}

result &lt;- make_risk_summary(participant_id = 31, age = 70, sbp = 145, at_risk = TRUE)
result

Participant 31 (age 70, SBP 145): AT RISK

153.4 Solve the Problem

participants &lt;- read.csv("data/participants.csv")

# Reuse Level 9's exact is_at_risk() definition and defaults
is_at_risk &lt;- function(age, sbp, age_cutoff = 65, bp_cutoff = 130) {
  age &gt;= age_cutoff & sbp &gt;= bp_cutoff
}

make_risk_summary &lt;- function(participant_id, age, sbp) {
  structure(
    list(participant_id = participant_id, age = age, sbp = sbp,
         at_risk = is_at_risk(age, sbp)),
    class = "risk_summary"
  )
}

print.risk_summary &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  status &lt;- if (x$at_risk) "AT RISK" else "not at risk"
  cat(sprintf("Participant %d (age %d, SBP %d): %s\n", x$participant_id, x$age, x$sbp, status))
}

row31 &lt;- participants[participants$id == 31, ]
result &lt;- make_risk_summary(row31$id, row31$age, row31$systolic_bp)
result

class(result)

Participant 31 (age 70, SBP 145): AT RISK
[1] "risk_summary"
Typing result at the console doesn’t print a raw list dump — it automatically calls print.risk_summary() instead, because R’s generic print() function checks an object’s class attribute first and dispatches to the matching method, exactly the mechanism behind Level 11’s tidy lm() printouts. Participant 31 is one of the exact 4 at-risk participants Level 9’s is_at_risk() identified, using its same default cutoffs (age ≥ 65, SBP ≥ 130).

154.1 The R Concept
tryCatch() runs a block of code and lets you specify exactly what should happen if it produces an error (or a warning), instead of letting it crash your script:
tryCatch({
  risky_code_that_might_fail()
}, error = function(e) {
  cat("Something went wrong:", conditionMessage(e), "\n")
  NA   # a fallback value to use instead
})
conditionMessage(e) extracts the actual error text, letting you report what went wrong rather than just that something did. The error = function(e) { ... } block only runs if an error actually occurs — otherwise, tryCatch() simply returns the result of the first block, unaffected.

154.2 Demonstration

safe_read_csv &lt;- function(path) {
  tryCatch({
    read.csv(path)
  }, error = function(e) {
    cat("Could not read", path, "-", conditionMessage(e), "\n")
    NULL
  })
}

